<methodology slug="video-generation-prompt-engineering">
  <metadata>
    <tier>geek</tier>
    <group>ai</group>
    <domain>ml-engineer</domain>
    <summary>Craft effective prompts for AI video generation using the Subject+Action+Setting+Style+Camera+Lighting formula, with provider-specific tips for Runway, Luma, Sora 2, and Veo 3.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>video-generation</tag>
      <tag>prompt-engineering</tag>
      <tag>runway</tag>
      <tag>luma</tag>
      <tag>veo</tag>
    </tags>
    <category>ai</category>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-27</created>
    <related>
      <ref slug="video-generation-provider-selection"/>
      <ref slug="video-generation-async-api"/>
      <ref slug="prompt-engineering-fundamentals"/>
    </related>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>AI Video Generation Prompt Engineering</title>

    <summary>Effective video generation prompts follow the formula: Subject + Action + Setting + Style + Camera + Lighting. Each provider processes prompts differently — Runway prefers cinematic camera directions while Luma prefers descriptive scene prose. Provider-specific prompt patterns yield significantly better results than generic descriptions.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Video generation models are trained on different data distributions and respond to different prompt patterns. A prompt that produces excellent results on Runway may be mediocre on Luma. Runway's model was trained on cinematic footage and responds to camera direction vocabulary (tracking shot, dolly, crane). Luma's model responds better to emotional and environmental descriptions. Veo 3 uniquely processes audio descriptions because it generates native audio. Without provider-specific prompting, agents waste expensive generation credits on poor-quality output that must be regenerated.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Writing prompts for any video generation provider (Runway, Luma, Sora 2, Veo 3, Replicate).</item>
        <item>Creating prompt templates for automated content pipelines (news B-roll, social media, product videos).</item>
        <item>Optimizing existing prompts that produce inconsistent or low-quality output.</item>
        <item>Building a prompt library for reuse across agent workflows.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Prompting for precise multi-shot character consistency — current models drift across clips regardless of prompt quality; use image seeding as a supplement.</item>
        <item>Controlling native audio content in Sora 2 or Veo 3 — audio is non-deterministic and cannot be controlled via prompt.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="prompt-formula">
      <p>Basic prompt formula:</p>
      <term name="formula">Subject + Action + Setting + Style + Camera + Lighting</term>

      <example type="good" title="Full formula applied">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
A golden retriever running through a field of sunflowers,
natural outdoor setting, cinematic film style,
tracking shot following the dog, warm golden hour lighting
]]></code>
        <note>All six components present: subject (golden retriever), action (running), setting (sunflowers field), style (cinematic film), camera (tracking shot), lighting (golden hour).</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="prompt-components">
      <p>Component vocabulary for each dimension:</p>

      <term name="subject">
        People: A young woman with red hair. An elderly man with a beard. A group of children.
        Animals: A majestic white horse. A curious orange cat. A flock of birds.
        Objects: A vintage red car. A steaming cup of coffee. A floating glass sphere.
      </term>

      <term name="action">
        Movement: walking slowly, running fast, dancing gracefully, flying through the air, swimming underwater, spinning, jumping, falling.
        Behavior: laughing joyfully, looking contemplatively, reaching toward the camera, transforming into particles.
      </term>

      <term name="setting">
        Natural: in a dense forest, on a sandy beach, in a mountain meadow, underwater in the ocean, floating in clouds, in a wheat field.
        Urban: on a busy city street, in an empty subway station, on a rooftop at night, in a neon-lit alley.
        Abstract: in a void of light, surrounded by floating shapes, in a surreal dreamscape.
      </term>

      <term name="style">
        Cinematic: cinematic film style, movie quality, blockbuster visual style, Hollywood production.
        Photography: documentary style, raw footage, photorealistic, hyperrealistic.
        Artistic: anime style, Studio Ghibli inspired, oil painting come to life, watercolor animation.
        Vintage: 8mm film grain, VHS aesthetic, black and white film noir, 1970s Kodak film look.
      </term>

      <term name="camera">
        Movement types: tracking shot, dolly shot, crane shot, handheld camera, steadicam, orbiting around subject, push in slowly, pull back dramatically.
        Angles: low angle looking up, high angle looking down, eye level, bird's eye view, dutch angle, extreme close-up.
      </term>

      <term name="lighting">
        Natural: golden hour sunlight, soft morning light, harsh midday sun, overcast diffused light.
        Artificial: neon lights, candlelight, spotlight, rim lighting, dramatic chiaroscuro.
        Atmospheric: foggy atmosphere, dust particles in light, volumetric god rays, underwater caustics.
      </term>
    </section>

    <section name="use-case-templates">
      <p>Prompt templates for common production use cases:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Product video template">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# Template:
[Product] elegantly rotating on a [surface],
[lighting type] lighting highlighting [features],
smooth 360-degree rotation, [background description],
commercial photography style, 4K quality

# Filled example:
A luxury watch elegantly rotating on a black marble surface,
soft studio lighting highlighting the gold accents,
smooth 360-degree rotation, dark gradient background,
commercial photography style, 4K quality
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Landscape/nature template">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# Template:
[Location description] at [time of day],
[weather/atmosphere], [camera movement],
[style reference], cinematic quality

# Filled example:
Mountain peaks emerging from sea of clouds at sunrise,
misty atmosphere with golden light, slow drone pullback,
National Geographic documentary style, cinematic quality
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Character/person template">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# Template:
[Person description] [action] in [setting],
[emotion/expression], [camera angle and movement],
[lighting], [style]

# Filled example:
Young woman with flowing dark hair walking through a rain-soaked city street,
contemplative expression looking up at the sky, tracking shot at eye level,
neon reflections on wet pavement, Blade Runner aesthetic
]]></code>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Social media vertical (9:16) template">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
# Template:
[Subject] [action], vertical 9:16 format,
[trending style], engaging motion,
[platform-appropriate style], high energy

# Filled example:
Colorful smoothie being poured in slow motion, vertical 9:16 format,
satisfying ASMR style, engaging swirling motion,
Instagram Reels aesthetic, vibrant colors
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="provider-specific-tips">
      <p>Provider-specific prompting strategies:</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For Runway Gen-3: use specific camera movement vocabulary (tracking shot, dolly, crane, orbiting), include motion speed descriptors (slow, fast, smooth), and use image input for style reference when character consistency matters.</statement>
        <rationale>Runway's model was trained heavily on cinematic footage. Camera direction vocabulary directly controls the camera system. Image-to-video mode reduces variance compared to text-only generation.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Prompt optimized for Runway">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
A person speaking to camera, natural head movements,
soft interview lighting, slight camera drift,
professional corporate video style
]]></code>
        <note>Runway excels at motion control, style transfer, lip-sync. Camera movement vocabulary has direct effect.</note>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For Luma Dream Machine: focus on subject and environment description, use emotional and sensory language, and minimize technical camera terminology. Luma responds better to descriptive scene prose than to cinematographic direction commands.</statement>
        <rationale>Luma's training distribution favors naturalistic scene descriptions. Emotional and sensory language activates more consistent motion patterns than technical camera commands.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Prompt optimized for Luma">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
A child discovering a butterfly in a sunlit garden,
wonder and curiosity, soft natural lighting,
warm nostalgic feeling, gentle movement
]]></code>
        <note>Luma excels at natural motion, landscapes, character consistency. Emotional descriptions work better than camera directions.</note>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For Sora 2: write multi-subject and complex scene descriptions with temporal transitions (starting with X, gradually transitioning to Y). Sora understands complex interactions and can handle multi-stage prompts for extension workflows.</statement>
        <rationale>Sora 2's architecture handles longer temporal sequences and complex scene physics. Temporal language activates its understanding of change over time within the clip.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Prompt optimized for Sora 2">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
A busy coffee shop scene, multiple patrons reading and chatting,
barista preparing drinks in background, natural ambient movement,
realistic physics, documentary observation style, 30 seconds
]]></code>
        <note>Sora 2 excels at long-form (up to 60s), complex scenes, physics accuracy. Can handle multiple simultaneous subjects.</note>
      </example>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>For Veo 3: include audio and sound descriptions alongside visual content, and specify resolution (4K). Veo 3 is the only model that processes audio descriptions to generate synchronized audio tracks.</statement>
        <rationale>Veo 3 uniquely generates native audio; audio descriptions activate this capability. Resolution specification triggers 4K output when available through Vertex AI.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Prompt optimized for Veo 3">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Two people having a conversation at outdoor cafe,
ambient street sounds, natural dialogue,
4K photorealistic quality, shallow depth of field
]]></code>
        <note>Veo 3 excels at 4K quality, native audio, photorealism. Audio descriptions are unique to this provider.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="negative-prompts">
      <p>Use negative prompts to exclude unwanted elements:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Quality exclusions: blurry, low quality, distorted faces, unnatural movement, glitchy artifacts, oversaturated, underexposed.</item>
        <item>Content exclusions: watermark, text overlay.</item>
        <item>Style exclusions: cartoon style, anime style (when wanting realism), CGI look (when wanting photorealistic).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="advanced-techniques">
      <p>Advanced prompt patterns for complex scenarios:</p>

      <example type="good" title="Temporal transition prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Starting with a closed flower bud at dawn,
gradually transitioning to full bloom as sunlight increases
]]></code>
        <note>Temporal language (starting with, gradually transitioning to) works best with Sora 2 which handles longer-form temporal sequences.</note>
      </example>

      <example type="good" title="Style mixing prompt">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[
Combine cyberpunk neon aesthetics with traditional Japanese garden elements,
cherry blossoms glowing with holographic shimmer
]]></code>
        <note>Style mixing works best with providers that have broad training distribution (Sora 2, Veo 3).</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="common-mistakes">
      <p>Common prompt mistakes and fixes:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Too vague ("A nice video of nature") — specify subject, location, time, style.</item>
        <item>Conflicting styles ("Realistic anime") — choose one dominant style.</item>
        <item>Too complex (multiple unrelated elements) — focus on one clear concept.</item>
        <item>No motion (static description) — add action verbs and camera movement.</item>
        <item>Wrong format (landscape for TikTok) — match aspect ratio to platform (9:16 for vertical, 16:9 for landscape).</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <checklist>
      <check>Include all six components: subject, action, setting, style, camera, lighting.</check>
      <check>Start prompt with clear subject identification.</check>
      <check>Add specific action/movement verbs — static descriptions produce static video.</check>
      <check>Specify visual style explicitly to avoid random style variation.</check>
      <check>Include camera movement description appropriate to the provider.</check>
      <check>Set lighting conditions to control mood and atmosphere.</check>
      <check>Match aspect ratio to target platform (16:9 landscape, 9:16 vertical).</check>
      <check>Keep complexity within a single concept — multi-subject complexity degrades quality.</check>
      <check>Add negative prompts to exclude watermarks, text overlay, and quality issues.</check>
      <check>Apply provider-specific vocabulary: camera directions for Runway, scene prose for Luma, audio for Veo 3.</check>
    </checklist>

